{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588357"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:06:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:06:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15130"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15130"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.08,0.08,0.23,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69320"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7818"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15130"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54774"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"403"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2012"},{"type":"tags","id":"2585"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"6376"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"9750"},{"type":"tags","id":"10521"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19058"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19062"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69320"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three days of fever, right flank pain, and dysuria. She has type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. Her medications include metformin and perindopril. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. She has marked right costovertebral angle tenderness. Urinalysis shows leucocytes, nitrites, and protein.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about pyelonephritis is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Emphysematous pyelonephritis predominantly affects patients with diabetes","Renal abscess typically has a more rapid onset than acute pyelonephritis","Blood cultures are unnecessary if urine cultures are positive","Oral antibiotics are appropriate first-line therapy for all cases","Imaging is required before starting antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a typical picture of acute pyelonephritis with fever, flank pain, and urinary symptoms. The presence of diabetes is particularly relevant as it increases the risk of complicated infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmphysematous pyelonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E is indeed a severe infection characterized by gas formation in the renal parenchyma, occurring predominantly in patients with diabetes mellitus. The high glucose environment and impaired immune response in diabetic patients facilitate gas-forming bacterial infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E typically has a more indolent course compared to acute pyelonephritis, not a more rapid onset. It often develops as a complication of untreated or inadequately treated pyelonephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegarding \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E, these should be obtained in all patients with suspected pyelonephritis requiring hospitalisation, regardless of urine culture results, as bacteraemia is common and can influence treatment duration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are appropriate for mild cases in reliable patients, but severe cases or those with complicating factors (such as diabetes) often require initial intravenous therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImaging\u003C/strong\u003E is not required before initiating antibiotics in straightforward cases. However, imaging should be considered in patients with undifferentiated or severe illness, those who fail to improve with appropriate therapy, or when complications are suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute pyelonephritis typically presents with fever, flank pain, and urinary symptoms.","Emphysematous pyelonephritis is a severe infection characterized by gas in the renal parenchyma, most commonly affecting patients with diabetes.","Renal abscess typically has an insidious onset compared to acute pyelonephritis."],"references":["Kumar S, Ramachandran R, Mete U, Mittal T, Dutta P, Kumar V, Rathi M, Jha V, Gupta KL, Sakhuja V, Kohli HS. Acute pyelonephritis in diabetes mellitus: Single center experience. Indian J Nephrol. 2014 Nov;24(6):367-71. doi: 10.4103/0971-4065.135347. PMID: 25484530; PMCID: PMC4244716.","Sabih A, Leslie SW. Complicated Urinary Tract Infections. 2023 Nov 12. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613784","Bilsen MP, Jongeneel RMH, Schneeberger C, Platteel TN, van Nieuwkoop C, Mody L, Caterino JM, Geerlings SE, K\u00f6ves B, Wagenlehner F, Conroy SP, Visser LG, Lambregts MMC. Definitions of Urinary Tract Infection in Current Research: A Systematic Review. Open Forum Infect Dis. 2023 Jun 27;10(7):ofad332. doi: 10.1093/ofid/ofad332. PMID: 37426954; PMCID: PMC10323732","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54774"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15130"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54774"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:32:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:37:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7818"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69320"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"update